			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Song upgrades, what upgrades?<a name="13950"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Dec 28 03 2:52 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Let's look at this in terms of haste songs:
<br />

<br />
At level 60, your choice of main haste song is between Vilia's Verses of Celerity and McVaxius' Rousing Rondo.  Vilia's is 45% group haste, no stats, good for when you lack an enchanter's haste.  Compare this to McV's, which is a much smaller haste but includes STR and ATK buffs and a DS component.  It is better for grouping with an enchanter or other main haster.
<br />

<br />
Now let's look at what you get at level 62 from an ethereal parchment turn-in:  Warsong of Zek.  It is 60% group haste and is also a buff to STR and ATK and a DS.  In other words, this song is like slamming Vilia's and McV's together at 900mph in a nuclear fusion reactor.  The difference is huge:  with a decent brass instrument modifier, WoZ can crank out some crazy ATK and DS numbers considering that it is only a single song in your twist.  It's far more effective at being a haste or a buff song than any of its predecessors.
<br />

<br />
Now let's look in terms of overhaste and spell focusing:
<br />

<br />
At level 60, you have access to Warsong of the Vah Shir (25% overhaste, exceeds cap, and has a better duration than most bard songs) and Composition of Ervaj (10% stacking haste that does not exceed the cap and a minor AC buff).  If you've done some LDoN, you may also have access Rizlona's Fire, a random 0-30% DD focus that nukers will adore.  That's all well and good, but if you want to buff your group to the max with this line, you're looking at twisting at least two (maybe three) songs from this category alone.
<br />

<br />
And then, at level 64, you get Rizlona's Call of Flame (cross your fingers on the spectral parchment turn-in).  This song is 30% overhaste, beyond the cap, and it is also a random 0-30% DD focus.  One song now takes care of the functions of the entire preceding line from the 50s (the additional 5% haste from Ervaj is pretty negligible since it doesn't raise the cap, as melees at this level start hitting the cap pretty easily with their nifty haste items plus WoZ or an enc haste.  Its AC component is generally negligible as well).  At 65, if you've been in love with LDoN like I have, you can get Call of the Muse, which is the exact same thing as Rizlona's Call of Flame except that it ALSO has a random 0-30% DoT focus component.  That's three awesome DPS-boosting effects in one song, as opposed to the multiple songs that are necessary to achieve anything like it at a lower level.
<br />

<br />
Now let's look in terms of damage shields and resists:
<br />

<br />
At level 60 you have access to your AE chorus resists.  Elemental Chorus and Purifying Chorus are both extremely useful raid songs and I have no intention of saying a single bad thing about either of them.  You also have access to the five basic Psalms, which will buff <i>one</i> resist stat very nicely (especially with a singing mod boost) while giving your group a fair DS.  This is pretty nice.
<br />

<br />
And then at level 63 you become the GOD of resist batteries, courtesy of a spectral parchment song.  Psalm of Veeshan adds huge resist bonuses to ALL FIVE resists at once.  With a good singing mod you can single-handedly pump a decently-geared group's resists to near the 500 cap.  It is also a DS of the same strength as your previous psalms.  Don't forget Warsong of Zek with its DS component.  With 2.4 mod (1.8 from Troubador's Mace or Epic, .6 from IM3), you can tack on an additional 36 point DS with little effort.  If you stack a decently modified Psalm of Veeshan and Warsong of Zek together, the amount of DS you create with quickly surpass that attainable by a mage or druid--and it will <i>stack</i> with theirs!!
<br />

<br />
Now let's look at Chants:
<br />
Instead of being longwinded again, I'll just refer you to the song list:
<br />
<a target="_new" href="http://www.dotnetdiva.com/eq/songlist.aspx">http://www.dotnetdiva.com/eq/songlist.aspx</a>
<br />
Even without instrument modifiers, the damage/tick from the 61+ chant line blows the old chants out of the water.  With a good percussion mod (and all the upgraded chants, which I admit can be a pain to get), you're looking at dealing obscene amounts of DoT with a 4 chant twist.  And as for Fufil's Curtailing Chant being dinky on damage, try the level 60 Fufil's Diminishing Dirge from Tak LDoN.  It deals damage that is equivalent to the 61+ chants and debuffs MR like mad.
<br />

<br />
Now let's look at the issue of Wind/Chorus of Marr giving a maximum of 20 mana per tick:
<br />

<br />
So what?  That mana regen is up there with KEI and VoQ and it <i>stacks</i> with them.  It is over twice as good as Spiritual Dominion, and it stacks with it as well!  The HP regen component from Wind/Chorus of Marr is huge, especially with a good modifier, and it can reduce the amount of mana necessary for healing if utilized properly.  Marr is also very good at giving shamans a steady Canni supply, and it is great for keeping necros healthy during Lich or for healing mod rod damage.  In other words, with the kind of FT and other mana regen buffs that casters are running around with, our mana should be a good bit of help but doesn't need to be better than 20 per tick.
<br />

<br />
Therefore, bard song upgrades do not suck.  QED.
<br />

<br />
On the subject of bards deserving a PBAE stun:
<br />

<br />
No way.  PBAE stun should be reserved for the enchanter.  It would be far too powerful for bards to be able to run up and slam crowds with stuns, especially if their durations were long at all.  We can already do a PBAE 45% slow (admittedly with a DoT component that prevents mez) to buy time when huge pulls occur.  We also have deftdance to protect us from large groups of mobs that are trying to kill our faces off while we're trying to mez them.  Enchanters do not, so they need PBAE stuns to compensate.
<br />

<br />
As far losing our stamina regen effects...how often were they really useful?  For me at least, they certainly weren't useful enough to have PBAE stuns given to us as a replacement.
<br />

<br />
Conclusion:
<br />

<br />
Bards are not meant to be the absolute best at doing everything, or even good at doing everything (especially trying to do it all at once).  Our forte lies in making the other classes better at what <i>they</i> do, filling in holes in a group's abilities when needed.  We take melees and make them swing faster and harder.  We take tanks and give them insane DSes and (if we like) AC boosts.  We take nukers/DoTers and make their spells hurt even more.  We give anyone with a mana bar a better mana supply.  We facilitate healing by providing HP regen and resists.  We help manage mobs using lulls, mezes, and slows.  We make escape or travel quicker and safer.  We make soloing look ridiculously easy.  Best of all, we can change these effects on the fly, remapping our twists to suit a changing situation.
<br />

<br />
Good bards are like good business managers:  they make sure the job gets done smoothly, quickly, and efficiently.  Though their assistance is usually indirect, they're always giving their support.  They are also rare.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%">Melees love us for the haste; casters love us for the mana; fleeing loonies love us for the Selo's.<br>
---Bard Motto<br>
<a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=910907>Lenowill's Magelo profile</a></span></td>
			</tr><tr>
