		<td class="PanelBody" nowrap="nowrap" valign="Top" width="150"><table border="0">
			<tr>
				<td><img src="/skins/default/images/user_IsOffline.gif" alt="Lenowill is not online. Last active: 9/27/2004 1:05:05 PM" border="0" />&nbsp;<a class="SmallBoldText" href="/User/UserProfile.aspx?UserName=Lenowill">Lenowill</a><br></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td><span class="SmallText"><b>Joined:</b> 18 Oct 2002</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td><span class="SmallText"><b>Total Posts: </b>105</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td>&nbsp;</td>
			</tr>
		</table></td><td class="PanelBody" valign="Top"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="0" width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Song upgrades, what upgrades?<a name="13984"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Dec 29 03 12:23 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Could you tell <i>which</i> songs you're talking about when you say &quot;our shield series&quot; gets weaker?  I don't follow you on that; I don't even know what stat is going from 20 to 10.  If there really is such a case then we probably need to /bug it.
<br />

<br />
And now, allow me to rebut some of Thott's arguments from <a target="_new" href="http://www.afterlifeguild.org/Thott/retune.php">http://www.afterlifeguild.org/Thott/retune.php</a>
<br />

<br />
Before I start, though, I'd like to point out that Thott's arguments are old.  They seem to be from the Luclin era (&quot;And now what do we see in Luclin?&quot;).  Many things have changed since then.
<br />

<br />
Let's discuss the subject of Bards being &quot;out-parsed&quot; (i.e. dealing less DPS, or damage per second) than other classes.
<br />

<br />
DPS is a beautiful thing.  To prove the worth of the bard class (and enchanters and shamans for that matter), I feel it is important to think of DPS in terms of two factors:  direct DPS and indirect DPS.
<br />

<br />
I define direct DPS as any damage dealt by a character solely as a result of his own attacks, spells, and buff effects of his own, cast on himself only.  In other words, bards have a very low direct DPS rating, with our highest coming from our chants.  Even though we can wreak serious havoc with those, there's not much that's spectacular about directly-generated bard DPS.
<br />

<br />
And then we get to indirect DPS, and suddenly bards are one of the strongest classes in the game.  I define indirect DPS as any increase in DPS that another character receives as a result of a buff or action from another character.
<br />

<br />
Before I give my examples, bear with me on these given rules:
<br />
Lenowill's First Rule of DPS:  Any time not actively spent in combat with mobs attempting to deal damage to them has a DPS of zero damage/sec.
<br />

<br />
Lenowill's Second Rule of DPS:  Accurate average DPS calculations <i>must</i> take periods of zero DPS (i.e. downtime) into account.
<br />

<br />
Lenowill's Third Rule of DPS:  In the end, it really doesn't matter which group member is <i>directly</i> causing damage to happen as long as the group pumps out damage well enough to eliminate downtime.  Therefore, when setting up a group, it is better to look at indirect DPS increases that occur due to interactions among classes.
<br />

<br />
Typical examples of indirect DPS from grouping:
<br />
-An enchanter/bard/shaman gives a melee character a haste buff.  Any DPS gained from the haste should be credited to the enchanter/bard/shaman when determining overall DPS value.  This is the DPS-increasing aspect of haste buffs.
<br />

<br />
-A warrior keeps mobs from hitting anyone but himself, preventing the cleric from having to heal the less-armored characters and preventing downtime.  He may also allow casters to nuke harder and more safely.  This is the DPS-increasing aspect of aggro management.
<br />

<br />
-A warrior turns a mob so that the pets have the mob's backside.  Any DPS increase due to the pets not getting parried/dodged/riposted/killed by enrage counts toward the warrior's indirect DPS.  He also ensures that the mob is never pressed into a corner, allowing for flawless melee action against its backside.  This is the DPS-increasing aspect of good mob positioning.
<br />

<br />
-The puller for a group (perhaps a bard) keeps the mobs coming, preventing any unnecessary downtime by ensuring that the group is constantly in combat unless a med break is needed.  This is the DPS-increasing aspect of steady pulling.
<br />

<br />
-A druid roots a mob that's about to try to eat the cleric.  The cleric can continue medding and does not have to waste mana healing herself.  Also, she is able to heal the tank when he needs it and thereby prevents a drop in DPS by avoiding downtime (from death or low mana).  Because he rooted the mob, the druid gets credit for that increase in DPS.  This is the DPS-increasing aspect of crowd control.
<br />

<br />
-A tank is wearing a bunch of uber gear and is taking (comparatively) tiny damage from the mobs.  The cleric only rarely has to heal him and even has enough mana to drop the occasional nuke and melee.  The tank has increased DPS by preventing downtime (through his AC and high HP count).  His tanking also happens to be good enough that the cleric literally has too much mana, allowing her to do things other than healing (a phenomenon I like to call &quot;overtime&quot;).
<br />

<br />
-An enchanter in PoK sells a wizard a hit of KEI, and the wizard goes and joins a group that lacks an enchanter.  The wizard has a nice boost to his mana regen, allowing him to nuke more often, translating to an increase in DPS.  The DPS increase, then, is attributed to the out-of-group enchanter (even though the wizard's group is given credit for it).  This is the DPS-increasing aspect of outside buffing.
<br />

<br />
-<b>A bard</b> sings a nice song named Call of the Muse in his group with a warrior, a rogue, a monk, a druid, and a cleric.  The warrior, rogue, monk, and cleric (if she's meleeing) gain a 30% overhaste effect.  Their melee DPS ratings increase.  The druid nukes or casts a DoT on the mob.  His spells are focused by Call of the Muse, meaning that the bard is indirectly adding an average of 15% damage to eat nuke or tick of DoT.  The amount of indirect DPS that bards can deal with this song is absolutely immense...and that's just one song!  This is one of the many DPS-increasing aspects of a well-played and well-twisting bard.
<br />

<br />
Bards are, hands down, the mighty kings of indirect DPS, with enchanters and shamans coming in as runners-up.  As I expressed in my previous post, bards have numerous means of increasing group DPS.  Usually, the bard isn't increasing his own DPS--but he's vastly increasing the DPS of his groupmates!  This means that a bard's overall DPS is largely determined by how powerful the other characters in his group happen to be.  If he's grouped with a bunch of wimps, then his indirect DPS increase will be slight.  If he's grouped with powerful characters, then his DPS goes through the roof--once you take indirect DPS into account.  People talk all the time about parsing individual DPS, and they whine constantly about not being as individually strong as random_class03, but really, who care's where the damage is coming from as long as it's there?  So what if I'm &quot;out-parsed&quot; by a rogue in my group?  I can rest assured that <i>I</i> am part of the reason his DPS is so good.
<br />

<br />
Therefore, our DPS does not suck.  QED.  We are by no means out of balance when it comes to putting the hurt on mobs, not because we are an army of one, but rather because we are the ones who harness and <i>increase</i> the power of a force of many.
<br />

<br />
Now let's talk about Thott's graphs.
<br />

<br />
My biggest argument against everything Thott is saying with his graphs is that he appears to be looking at the problem in terms of ONE SONG versus the most effective single spell of another class.  This is a dire mistake, as any bard worth his salt knows that twisting songs together is the key to producing powerful effects.
<br />

<br />
Also, as Thott himself points out, his graphs lack instrument modifiers.  Instruments are the original focus items of EverQuest.  They are the workaday tools of the bard class.  They must be taken into account!
<br />

<br />
On the subject of the healing graph being a flat curve, I do believe he isn't being very creative with his healing songs.  Let's look just at the level 55 part of that graph:
<br />

<br />
At 55 we get a lovely song known as Cantata of Replenishment, the joy of late fifties groups around Norrath.  With no instrument modifier, this song heals 11 HP per tick.  Even I will admit that this isn't much.  Assuming a tick occurs every six seconds, you're looking at a measly 1.83 HP/sec from Cantata--just as Thott's graph shows.  But wait, let's stick a 1.8 mod lute onto it...nothing fancy.  It now heals 20 HP/tick (assuming the formula rounds properly), or 3.33 HP/sec.  That's still not a lot.
<br />

<br />
However, that's calculated using only one song.  He neglected to mention that, at level 47, we get a song known as Niv's Melody of Preservation that also increases HP regeneration.  By level 55, its regen increase would be about 7 HP/tick with no modifier, or 1.17 HP/sec.  Now let's stick a basic 1.8 stringed instrument mod on it...again, nothing fancy; I know how much of a pain those &quot;phat lutes&quot; (pun intended) can be to acquire.  The result is that Niv's Melody of Preservation now heals 13 HP/tick (assuming the formula rounds properly).  We're now looking at 2.17 HP/sec from Niv's alone--a total of 5.40 HP/sec once we add the value from the modified Cantata.
<br />

<br />
That's still less than a paladin.  But wait!  We can slow; a paladin cannot.  Neither can druids or clerics Our slows get better and better as we level up.  Slow reduces the DPS of a mob, and damage prevented is damage healed!  The same goes for Shield of Songs and Nillipus' March of the Wee, which are minor runes (though Shield of Songs does not stack with Niv's Melody of Preservation).
<br />

<br />
Also, let's think of bards in terms of grouping.  Assuming that every member of a bard's six-person party is hurt, the bard is no longer healing 5.40 HP/sec, but rather 32.4 HP/sec--and this is without mentioning the handy mana regen bonus from Cantata.  Yes, this means that bard healing, like any other group regen healing, is most effective when everyone is taking a bit of damage.
<br />

<br />
Hm.  Bards just jumped over clerics in terms of HP/sec!  Remember, though, this effect is over time rather than instantaneous like most clerical healing.  Also, the condition of my figures is that the bard must be twisting at least two &quot;healing&quot; songs with a 1.8 mod (or better), and the whole group has to be at less than 100% HP--this situation isn't exactly common, and it limits haste twisting options. Then again, if you're going to be the healer for a group, then you're not in a common situation anyway, so you might as well get creative!
<br />

<br />
Bards do not stagnate in healing ability with level.  On the contrary, our ability to regenerate group HP or prevent its loss goes up pretty dramatically--but it only does so when you look at the whole picture rather than at a single song.  Alas, you can't have a symphony orchestra with just a wind section!
<br />

<br />
The same is basically true for the rest of Thott's graphs, and I think I've already beaten the subject of our DPS into the ground, so I'll move on.
<br />

<br />
On the subject of slows, poisons, and disease and our apparent inability to cure them:
<br />

<br />
We can.  Use Aria of Asceticism from LoY.  It works like a charm.  I'm aware that Thott is talking about Psalm of Purity and Psalm of Vitality which were supposed to have disease- and poison-curing components.  Maybe they'll be fixed someday, but in the meantime, we have Asceticism, which does a darned nice job at curing Tash, slow...the works.  Aria of Innocence is also great as a curse remover.  They can also be twisted in without dropping four of the five Psalm of Veeshan uber-resists, whereas using Vitality or Purity to cure diseases/poisons would leave only one base covered.
<br />

<br />
On the subject of focus items/FT not affecting bards:
<br />

<br />
As I stated above, we have EQ's original focus items.  We have instruments.  Why would we need any others, especially considering what I've already stated about the nature of our class?  Also, FT -does- effect bards.  So what if our songs don't generally use mana?  Use Fading Memories a few times and you'll see why FT is such a lovely thing for us to have.
<br />

<br />
Yes, Denon's Desperate Dirge needs to be changed to be affected by singing mods.  That's a minor thing, though.
<br />

<br />
As for the &quot;Christmas light effect&quot;:  Yep, we don't have a snare that works on unslowable mobs.  Consider bringing a snaring class with you when you want to fight things that run but can't be slowed.  Yep, our mez pushes don't work on mez-immune mobs.  Instead, use Brusco's Boastful Bellow, Saryrn's Scream of Pain, or the Boastful Bellow AA to shove no-mez mobs around.  Or, perhaps, you could just tell your tank to reposition it.  If you're going for an interrupt, though (on CHeal or gate), keep shoving it with those songs and the AA bellow.
<br />

<br />
Conclusion:
<br />

<br />
Sorry, but we're not underpowered.  Please do explain what you mean by &quot;our shield line&quot; and its getting progressively worse.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
